{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611830"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16246"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.12,0.76,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65154"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8937"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50590"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"9924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21270"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65154"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following parameters is typically higher in children compared to adults?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Systolic blood pressure","Haemoglobin concentration","Respiratory rate","Serum creatinine","Body temperature"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding normal vital sign ranges across different age groups is crucial for clinical assessment. \u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory rate\u003C/strong\u003E is notably higher in children compared to adults, with newborns having a normal rate of 30-60 breaths per minute, which gradually decreases with age until reaching adult values of 12-20 breaths per minute by adolescence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystolic blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is actually lower in children and increases gradually with age. A rough guide for expected systolic blood pressure in children aged 1-10 years is 90 + (2 \u00d7 age in years) mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin concentration\u003C/strong\u003E varies with age but is generally lower in children compared to adults. Newborns have high levels at birth (140-240 g/L) which drops to their lowest point at 2-3 months (94-130 g/L), known as the nadir, then gradually increases but remains below adult levels until adolescence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum creatinine\u003C/strong\u003E is lower in children due to their smaller muscle mass. Adult reference ranges are not applicable to children, and values increase gradually with age and muscle development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBody temperature\u003C/strong\u003E regulation is similar in children and adults, with a normal range of 36.5-37.5\u00b0C. While children may be more susceptible to temperature changes, their baseline temperature is not typically higher than adults.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal respiratory rate is higher in children than adults, decreasing with age from birth to adolescence.","Understanding age-specific vital sign ranges is crucial for accurate assessment of paediatric patients.","Physiological differences between children and adults reflect developmental changes in organ systems."],"references":["Reuter S, Moser C, Baack M. Respiratory distress in the newborn. Pediatr Rev. 2014 Oct;35(10):417-28; quiz 429. doi: 10.1542/pir.35-10-417. PMID: 25274969; PMCID: PMC4533247.","Fleming S, Thompson M, Stevens R, Heneghan C, Pl\u00fcddemann A, Maconochie I, Tarassenko L, Mant D. Normal ranges of heart rate and respiratory rate in children from birth to 18 years of age: a systematic review of observational studies. Lancet. 2011 Mar 19;377(9770):1011-8. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(10)62226-X. PMID: 21411136; PMCID: PMC3789232.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50590"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16246"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50590"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T16:40:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T16:41:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8937"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65154"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"h